00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:22.260
The classification of Middle
Easterners and North Africans

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:26.700
in the US as white by race
stretches back over a century ago.

00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:30.490
In light of the possibility that
there might be a new Middle Eastern

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:32.750
and North African box, MENA box,

00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:35.820
and I'll use that acronym
throughout my presentation,

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:37.790
on the 20/20 census form.

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:41.950
This historical research has
contemporary significance.

00:04:41.950 --> 00:04:44.440
In today's presentation,
we will learn that debates

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:48.000
of the MENA racial
classifications are not novel,

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.160
and that a deeper examination
of history and critique

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:55.350
of historical narratives offers
the contemporary reader 3

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:58.450
noteworthy insights.

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:04.780
Firstly, the naturalization
rulings in US courts

00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:10.090
that determine the eligibility of
early MENA's to US citizenship show

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:14.480 position:56%
that labels of the geographic
region and the perceptions of people

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:16.610
within them determined race.

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:20.210
While they're ultimately classified
as white, and therefore grouped

00:05:20.210 --> 00:05:24.630
with Europeans, those with
Middle Eastern origins were noted

00:05:24.630 --> 00:05:28.950
as from Asia in terms of
Continental assignments,

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:33.950
but not ultimately Asiatic
or Mongolian by race.

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:36.660
Secondly, I will show
that the judges

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:42.120
in these cases drew a Christian
Muslim binary and placed a premium

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:46.270
on their origins in the Mohammed
world, as it was called back then.

00:05:46.270 --> 00:05:50.610
Occasionally noting the Eastern
rites of their Christianity,

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:55.060
and generally grouping Syrian
Christians with Islam by culture,

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:59.740
even if they were recognized
as Christian.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:04.670
Finally, the history of the US
Census classifications indicates

00:06:04.670 --> 00:06:09.310 position:56%
that MENA's have been identified by
factors other than race and religion

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:14.810
on official forms issued by the
US government for over a century,

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:18.360
specifically through
questions relating to ancestry

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.440
and language spoken at home.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.570
In other words, then is now.

00:06:22.570 --> 00:06:25.710
There are additional ways
to access ethnic identity

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:28.970
within a broad racial white
racial classification.

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:30.910
So it's a bit of background.

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:33.870
Since 1977, the US government
and particularly the Office

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:36.810
of Management and Budget has
classified white as a person --

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:41.150
in quotes, "a person having origins
in any of the original peoples

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:45.190
of Europe, the Middle
East, or North Africa."

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:49.030
Although geographic boundaries
of the MENA region are undefined,

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:52.570
I consider the main ethnic
groups in MENA to be Iranians,

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:55.580
Persians, Turks, and Arabs.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:58.100
But the region also
includes significant numbers

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:02.860
of minority ethnic groups,
namely the Armazi, the Kurds,

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:05.840
and Armenians, as wells
as ethno-religious groups,

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:12.470 position:56%
including Chadians, Assyrians,
Syriacs, Maronites, cults, and Jews.

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:17.000
And often language is tied to
each one of these collectivities.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.330
This presentation will focus on
how people from all of these groups

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:23.960
from the MENA region came to be
classified by the US government

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:26.920
in official records
before World War II.

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:31.270
Racially, they were classified as
white in 2 batches of legal cases.

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:37.380
The first set, by Syrian
Christians, between 1909 in 1915.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.990
And the second set,
by Muslim Arabians.

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:41.770
These are terms that
were used in these cases.

00:07:41.770 --> 00:07:45.180
In 1942 and '44.

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:49.980
Through an examination of
immigration categories,

00:07:49.980 --> 00:07:53.800
census questions, and racial
prerequisite cases, legal cases,

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:57.870
I will strive to highlight how
geography, race, and religion were,

00:07:57.870 --> 00:08:01.040
in fact, intertwined,
and provide insights

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:05.010
into how mainstream American
society viewed MENA Americans

00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:08.300
as between white and nonwhite.

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.060
So I wanted to ask
you as the audience

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:15.950 position:56%
if there was ever a time you've been
mistaken for a member of an ethnic,

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:19.580
religious, or national group
that you did not belong to.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:22.360
And how did that make you feel.

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:24.820 position:56%
If you felt that it was a compliment

00:08:24.820 --> 00:08:31.120
and positive mistaken
identity, put up your hands.

00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:32.420
Okay, nice, 3.

00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:34.420
And if you felt that it
was something that hurt you

00:08:34.420 --> 00:08:38.550
or is negative, put up your hands.

00:08:38.550 --> 00:08:40.230
Okay, so about even.

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:45.040
We're going to talk a
little bit about that today.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:53.800
Sorry. Okay, so in the first
sort of phase of immigration,

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:58.260 position:56%
you had the Philadelphia, there were
men from North Africa who traveled

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:00.770 position:56%
or were brought to the US as slaves.

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:05.780
The Philadelphia World's Fair of
1876 brought people and delegations

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:10.370 position:56%
from the Ottoman Empire, Egypt, and
Tunisia to showcase their countries.

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:13.470
The Ottoman exhibit heavily
featured Palestinian Christians

00:09:13.470 --> 00:09:16.580
from Bethlehem and Jerusalem
who were marketed as being

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.600
from the Bible land
or the holy land,

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:22.020
with shepherds herding
the flocks and images

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:25.110
that were called the
Arabian nights fables.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:28.860
They sold religious items
such as olive wood crucifixes

00:09:28.860 --> 00:09:33.360
from Bethlehem, rosary beads, and
mother-of-pearl decorative items.

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:37.200
This was part of the Ottoman
Empire strategy to show the world

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:40.430
that they treated their
religious minorities with respect.

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:43.340
And yet there are media
reports, US media reports,

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:45.300
of surprise that there
were Christians

00:09:45.300 --> 00:09:47.460
who were Ottoman Turkish subjects.

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:49.850
Because Arabs and Turks
were perceived in the US

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:52.720
to be followers of Mohammed.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:56.650
Some of these merchants stayed
on such, as Joseph Abien Matter,

00:09:56.650 --> 00:10:01.760
who is recorded in the 1880
census as living in Philadelphia.

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:10.140 position:56%
so usually I'm just going to cite 5
reasons that are cited for the onset

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:16.160 position:56%
of the first phase of immigration
which began in 1880, or about there,

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:18.380
it's not an exact cutoff
date, of course.

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:24.010
And that these immigrants came
from Bilad Al-Sham, or Syria,

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:28.090
an Ottoman province that encompass
present-day Lebanon, Syria,

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:32.620
Palestine, Israel, and parts of
Jordan, and they came to the US.

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:36.630
The fair had prompted stories
of wealth and success to be had

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:41.960
from selling goods to Americans
and offered the lure of adventure.

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:46.450
Combined with the economic downturn
of the economy due to the collapse

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:50.430
of silk factories, or
sericulture, on Mount Lebanon,

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:54.100
the financial incentives of
living and earning money in the US

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:56.750
for a few years were strong.

00:10:56.750 --> 00:10:59.420
An argument I find
compelling is the influence

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:02.400
of the Christian missionaries
from the US establishing

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:05.290
and teaching schools in the region.

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:09.830
Also cited that, in my opinion,
less likely due to the dates,

00:11:09.830 --> 00:11:11.610
is the sectarian violence,

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:14.740
particularly the Drupe Maronite
clashes on Mount Lebanon,

00:11:14.740 --> 00:11:17.170
and the riots in Damascus.

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:21.010
However, the deterioration of the
Ottoman Empire and the conscription

00:11:21.010 --> 00:11:25.650
of young Christian and Jewish men
into the Army required in 1909

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:28.810
by the Ottoman Empire were
significant factors in the choice

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:32.910
of young men to move continents.

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:49.100
So I'm going to come back
to the issue of Mallets.

00:11:49.100 --> 00:11:53.540
Okay, this is a picture of the
Zainea family from Damascus,

00:11:53.540 --> 00:11:56.140
and this is when they
were there in Damascus.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:12:00.010
I believe that they are
possibly Orthodox, Rome,

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:02.240
or Roman Catholic Melkites.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:07.340
From their dress, they
were definitely urban,

00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:09.600
and probably elite.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:14.910
A little background though I want
to give you on the Ottoman Empire.

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:18.840
In 1516, the Ottoman Empire
is invaded Bilad Al-Sham,

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:22.440
and continued to rule almost
continuously until World War I.

00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:25.590
The Ottoman Empire gave Sunni
Muslims the primary place

00:12:25.590 --> 00:12:27.310
as socially and culturally superior

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:29.910
to the other communities
in the Empire.

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:34.080
In the 19th century, the
state solidified legal

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:37.150
and sociopolitical
structures for non-Muslims.

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:40.240
In these Millets, which I mentioned
on the last slide, Christian

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:43.900
and Jewish subjects were permitted
to regulate their own communities

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:47.500
and given some autonomy in
terms of family laws, taxation,

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:49.980
and collective representation.

00:12:49.980 --> 00:12:54.010
The largest Christian millet
in the 18th and 19th century,

00:12:54.010 --> 00:13:00.420
in the Syrian province, was the
Orthodox Christian or Rome Mallets.

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:03.720
You'd write it in English as RUM.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:07.230
According to their own
ecclesiastical structures,

00:13:07.230 --> 00:13:10.620
these Orthodox Christians
fell under 2 patriarchates,

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:13.000
the larger Greek-dominated
patriarchate,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.200 position:56%
or Sea of Constantinople, and the
smaller Arabic-speaking patriarchate

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:22.750 position:56%
of Antioch that was headquartered in
Damascus and had the areas now known

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:25.980
as Lebanon and Syria
under its jurisdiction.

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:31.040
In 1848, the Empire gave Greek
Catholics, called RUM Catholic

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:33.450
in Arabic, who were in union

00:13:33.450 --> 00:13:36.760
with the Roman Catholic
Church, a millet of their own.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:38.670
These Greek Catholics,
which, despite the name,

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:43.100
were explicitly Arabic speaking in
services, as well as colloquially,

00:13:43.100 --> 00:13:46.600
were also known as
malekites or King's men,

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:51.170
sir name for their loyalty to
the Byzantine Empires Emperors.

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:54.820
Roman Catholics who were not
part of the Melkites church

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:57.780
and Protestants were
granted extraordinary status

00:13:57.780 --> 00:14:00.670
as protected foreigners,
and Maronites

00:14:00.670 --> 00:14:02.980
and other Latin rites were
dealt with at the level

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:06.210
of the local provincial
administrations.

00:14:06.210 --> 00:14:08.850
This patchwork of treatment
gave religious minorities

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:12.010
in the Ottoman Empire a
degree of religious freedom,

00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:15.230
but they were also required
to submit to Ottoman demands

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:20.030
and the Islamic character
of the state or Empire.

00:14:20.030 --> 00:14:23.460
This is the backdrop against which
many of the immigrants arrived

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:26.360
in the US and perceived identity.

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:27.710
The Ottoman Millets

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:31.880
and decentralized system ingrained
identity as defined by religion,

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:35.390
broadly Christian, Jewish,
Muslim, and noted the differences

00:14:35.390 --> 00:14:40.520
between religious sects for
Christians, Roman Catholic,

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:44.220
Roman Catholic, Protestant,
and Maronite, for example.

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:47.570
And that underlined which
areas and sects were answerable

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:51.900
to which patriarchs, to which
religious figures, to which rabbis.

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:54.810
Whether or not the existence
of Mallets created the violence

00:14:54.810 --> 00:14:57.320
and discrimination against
Christians in Mount Lebanon

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:59.830 position:56%
or the riots in the city of Damascus

00:14:59.830 --> 00:15:03.260
in the late 19th century
became less important

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:07.010
for the immigrants upon their
arrival in their new countries

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:09.740
in South and North
America then the fact

00:15:09.740 --> 00:15:12.240
that they'd come from
the Ottoman Empire.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:17.880
So going back to my question,

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:23.830
the migrants from below Bilad
Al-Sham were recorded as Ottoman,

00:15:23.830 --> 00:15:28.060
or from Turkey in Asia, and
sometimes from Palestine or Syria,

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:31.220
in official immigration
records in the US,

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:36.580
until the end of the Ottoman Empire
officially dissolved in 1923.

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:40.500
Religion was not recorded and so
estimates of religious breakdowns

00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:44.820
of the Syrian migrants are
problematic, but we can assume

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:48.410
that many of the non-Turkish
Ottoman subjects might object

00:15:48.410 --> 00:15:50.860
to classification as Ottoman.

00:15:50.860 --> 00:15:54.870
Because Ottoman was seen
as synonymous with Turkish,

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:56.170
which was ethnically

00:15:56.170 --> 00:16:00.790 position:56%
and linguistically
differentiated from Arabic speakers.

00:16:00.790 --> 00:16:04.850
Back home, these immigrants had
informally used the term Turk

00:16:04.850 --> 00:16:06.260
to refer to Muslims.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:11.970
And in the US, Turk and even Syrian
connoted an Islamic identification.

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:14.700
This popular assumption in the US

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:19.380
in the early 19th century was
well-founded, was well illustrated

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:26.710
by a pulp fiction story that
appeared in the American Magazine

00:16:26.710 --> 00:16:33.010
in 1912 that I found nestled in the
NAF archives at the Smithsonian.

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:36.480
In the story, Emily, a
curious young farm girl,

00:16:36.480 --> 00:16:40.140
asked a self-described
peddler from Syria,

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:44.160
aren't they Mohammedans,
your people?

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:49.360
And when he explains that his
mother belonged to the Greek church

00:16:49.360 --> 00:16:52.760
but that he was Presbyterian,
Emily was incredulous.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:56.020
Emily was impressed with
how exotic this peddler was,

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:57.800
different from her
family in every way,

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:01.250
because of his backgrounds
in a far-off land.

00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:04.660
Even if he was Christian,
he seemed Mohammedan.

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:07.810
Today, of course, we do
not use the term Mohammedan

00:17:07.810 --> 00:17:09.750
because Muslims don't
worship Mohammad,

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:14.270
but back then it was sort
of standard practice.

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:18.110
The blurring of the East with Islam
follows a traditional Orientalist

00:17:18.110 --> 00:17:21.760
binary that posits the Orient
as defined in opposition

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:25.410
to the Occident and
Western Christianity.

00:17:25.410 --> 00:17:30.600
In his critique of
Orientalis, Edward Siad pointed

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:34.210
out that those Orientalist
scholars, such as Masagnul,

00:17:34.210 --> 00:17:38.180
saw Eastern Christians
as subsumed within Islam,

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:40.310
and as part of a monolithic East

00:17:40.310 --> 00:17:43.030
which had Islam as
the superstructure.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:46.140
At a time when the US was
increasingly xenophobic,

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:50.510
this association with Islamic
other was particularly problematic,

00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:53.630
especially for immigrants from the
East who wanted to gain material

00:17:53.630 --> 00:17:58.950
and social status in the US.

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:04.600
Alixa Naff, authored a
seminal history book called

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:07.430
"Becoming American, the
early Arab experience,"

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:10.160
and it was published in 1985.

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:14.090 position:56%
And it truly began a deeper interest
in the history of the Syrians,

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:17.370 position:56%
in particular, but Arabs in general.

00:18:17.370 --> 00:18:20.680
Though her book in large collection
is housed at the Smithsonian,

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:24.620
she initiated a dominant
narrative of the early experience

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:27.970
as she called it, meaning
before World War II.

00:18:27.970 --> 00:18:31.510
Within Arab-American studies, there
is a dominant historical narrative

00:18:31.510 --> 00:18:34.610
of the poor illiterate farmer
from a village in Mount Lebanon

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:37.150
or Syria who came to the US.

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:41.840
First arriving in New York at Ellis
Island, and then staying or living

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:46.870 position:56%
for a few days or possibly longer in
what was called the mother colony,

00:18:46.870 --> 00:18:51.700
which was the Syrian colony that
existed at the tip of Manhattan.

00:18:51.700 --> 00:18:55.610
And then that traveler would
possibly travel by train

00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:59.780
to meet family members or friends
and start peddling with the goods

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:05.480
that he bought, because most of
this discourse is for single men,

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:07.020
with the goods in New York.

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:12.460
This photo of a peddler is
somewhat iconic to that narrative.

00:19:12.460 --> 00:19:16.130
NAF estimated that as much
as 95% of the immigrants

00:19:16.130 --> 00:19:19.390
from Syria were Christian
before World War II.

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:23.530
While another historian
calculated that nearly 90%

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:28.420
of all Arabic-speaking immigrants
arriving the US before 1924 were

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:30.890
Syrian Christians from
Mount Lebanon.

00:19:30.890 --> 00:19:34.090
According to these historians,
the Arabic-speaking immigrants

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:37.530
to the US would have been
Christian with a minority

00:19:37.530 --> 00:19:39.940
of Drupe and Sunni Muslims.

00:19:39.940 --> 00:19:45.530
This is a young fellow
that is an example

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:49.510
that the dominant narrative does
contain some truths, in my mind.

00:19:49.510 --> 00:19:51.650 position:56%
Toufic here was all of those things.

00:19:51.650 --> 00:19:55.840
He was a single male
who immigrated in 1914.

00:19:55.840 --> 00:20:01.160
Was a Maronite Christian from
the village in Mount Lebanon,

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:02.460
Bqaatouta, east of Beirut.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:07.190 position:56%
He was a farmer in that village and
was unschooled, probably illiterate,

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:11.510 position:56%
and became a laborer and a peddler
in the US, where he changed his name

00:20:11.510 --> 00:20:15.400
by adding Ellis, after
his father Ellis.

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:19.070
In 1919, he opened a cigar
store with his uncle,

00:20:19.070 --> 00:20:24.560 position:56%
and later produced arak, an aniseed
flavored spirit, during prohibition.

00:20:24.560 --> 00:20:29.430
In 1925, Toufic returned to
Lebanon to fetch a bride.

00:20:29.430 --> 00:20:33.460 position:56%
Returning to the US a year later,
where he and his wife had his family

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:40.190
and lived out the rest
of their days.

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:42.750
This photo may represent
the marginalized narrative

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:44.760
of early Arab-American history.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:48.190
There is a dearth of information,
or even ongoing research,

00:20:48.190 --> 00:20:52.650 position:56%
regarding Egyptian, Iranian, Yemeni,
and North African immigrants.

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:56.150
This photo shows an
allegiance to the Ottoman Empire

00:20:56.150 --> 00:21:02.160
through the fezzes, which are the
hats that are shaped like a cone,

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:05.960
and the Star and Crescent on what
looks like to me a water pipe

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:11.140
or possibly a decorative silver
or brass vase, it's at the top

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:13.860
of the vase you can see the Star.

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:17.480
These were possibly
Egyptians, possibly Muslim.

00:21:17.480 --> 00:21:20.680
And the alternative
discourse I believe needs

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:22.200
to be further researched.

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:23.550
Who were these immigrants?

00:21:23.550 --> 00:21:27.260
How do they fit in or differ from
the narratives on the Syrians?

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:31.940
Why did their race never come
up in legal cases until the end,

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:40.910
where you hear Yemeni
debates, debates on the Yemeni?

00:21:40.910 --> 00:21:44.690
However, Syrian identity was
recognized in the US Census.

00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:49.360
In the 1900, 1910,
and 1920 censuses,

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:51.950
Syrian were a recognized group

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:54.900
within the population
statistics of foreign-born whites.

00:21:54.900 --> 00:22:02.000 position:56%
In the 1910 in 1920 censuses, Syria
was listed as a separate birthplace,

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:05.930
even though it was still officially
part of the Ottoman Empire.

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:10.040
During World War I, 1914
to 1918, being associated

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:13.030
with the Ottoman Empire became
more of a political problem rather

00:22:13.030 --> 00:22:15.610
than just an identification issue.

00:22:15.610 --> 00:22:20.090
Because the US sided with the
Allies against the Axis powers,

00:22:20.090 --> 00:22:22.420
including the Ottoman Empire.

00:22:22.420 --> 00:22:25.960 position:56%
This solidified a move away from
associations with the Ottoman Empire

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:29.880
for the Syrians, a shift
in identity, supported

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:33.000
and recognized by the
US Census Bureau.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:37.560
By 1930, the census, the
Ottoman Empire had collapsed,

00:22:37.560 --> 00:22:42.070
a new country of birth
appellations became necessary.

00:22:42.070 --> 00:22:45.530
The Census Bureau asked its
census takers or enumerators

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:47.550
to record the country
of birth according

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:51.480
to present geopolitical
locations in 1930.

00:22:51.480 --> 00:22:57.260
This is specifically mentioning,
as you can see, the list up there.

00:22:57.260 --> 00:23:00.450
This indicates to the researcher
that there were other types

00:23:00.450 --> 00:23:04.120
of MENA's present in the US
and that the Census Bureau was

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:07.140
also recognizing.

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:12.280
And another way that
Syrians were recognized was

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:15.260
through language spoken at
home, which was recorded.

00:23:15.260 --> 00:23:21.210
And the 1910 census asked, can
the person speak English, if not,

00:23:21.210 --> 00:23:24.390 position:56%
what language does the person speak.

00:23:24.390 --> 00:23:26.600
And both Syrian and
Turkish were listed

00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:31.600
as principal foreign languages
spoken in the US, but not Arabic.

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:34.880
I don't know the reason for that.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:37.260
But that's something
that is interesting.

00:23:37.260 --> 00:23:41.530 position:56%
And yet, in 1920, the options on the
respondent's mother tongue expanded

00:23:41.530 --> 00:23:46.600
to include Arabic, and
then again in 1930,

00:23:46.600 --> 00:23:49.280
the options included Egyptians.

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:57.720
So in 1930, they had
Syrian, Arabic, and Egyptian.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:01.050
However, the Syrian
community was not monolithic,

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:03.670
even if we just take it as Syrian.

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:13.880 position:56%
An Academic Philip Carey Hitti,
published a study in 1924 on Syrians

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:16.700
in America that found
that most were Christian.

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:19.800
Most numerous among the
Syrians were the Maronites,

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:22.940
followed by the Orthodox
and Greek Catholics,

00:24:22.940 --> 00:24:25.400
Melkites, and then Protestants.

00:24:25.400 --> 00:24:28.140
While these churches
indicated a healthy community,

00:24:28.140 --> 00:24:29.500
the divisions between sects

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:33.600
and nations were becoming
increasingly prevalent.

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:41.360 position:56%
New countries were being established
under colonial powers by the 1920,

00:24:41.360 --> 00:24:44.600
divided between British and
French colonial authorities.

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:52.420
Coming back to the US, in 1910, the
census enumerators were instructed

00:24:52.420 --> 00:24:54.780
to note down their nativity.

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:57.760
And if the respondent said
that their parents nativity was

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:04.800
in Turkey, they were asked
to note the Asia part.

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:08.490
Although the Syrian province is
located in Asia, they did not want

00:25:08.490 --> 00:25:12.150
to be considered Asian due to
the prevailing Asian exclusion

00:25:12.150 --> 00:25:15.430
and restrictions, which
were well-known.

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:20.860
Until 1909, MENA's had assumed
the privileges of whiteness.

00:25:20.860 --> 00:25:24.330
They were granted citizenship
without much deliberation.

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:26.240
They held political offices.

00:25:26.240 --> 00:25:29.240
And they owned property, even in
states where property ownership

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:37.060
by aliens was prohibited.

00:25:37.060 --> 00:25:41.160
The Naturalization era began --

00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:43.850
I'm moving but I'll
come back to this topic.

00:25:43.850 --> 00:25:47.680
The Naturalization era began
with the 1790 Naturalization Act,

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:50.670
which stipulated that only
free white persons could become

00:25:50.670 --> 00:25:51.970
US citizens.

00:25:51.970 --> 00:25:55.380
The racial designation as
white became a prerequisite

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:59.560
for naturalization and for
full rights as a US citizen.

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:04.350 position:56%
The question then became, who
qualified to be a free white person.

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:06.510
And this decision was
determined by the courts,

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:10.190
and in particular, by judges.

00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:15.210
Armenians, Mexicans, Indians, and
Sikhs all faced racial, and others,

00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:20.330
all faced racial prerequisite
cases between 1909 and 1923.

00:26:20.330 --> 00:26:23.890
But 1 in 3 racial prerequisite
cases heard

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:26.980
in the US federal courts
were of Syrians.

00:26:26.980 --> 00:26:30.610
Obviously this number far
exceeds the percentage of Syrians

00:26:30.610 --> 00:26:34.760 position:56%
or even MENA's in the US population,

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:37.390
indicating that the racial
ascription of Syrians was

00:26:37.390 --> 00:26:41.730
in question legally and
perhaps socially at the time.

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:45.130
After the Syrian Christians white
racial ascription had been finally

00:26:45.130 --> 00:26:49.540
determined in 1915, and
I'm going to go over these,

00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:52.980
in overturning the
case of George Dow,

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:56.180
other cases popped up in the 1940s.

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:58.410 position:56%
These were of 2 men who were Muslim.

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:02.490
One, an Amen man whose petition
for naturalization was rejected.

00:27:02.490 --> 00:27:06.240
And one of a Saudi whose petition

00:27:06.240 --> 00:27:09.160
to be naturalized in
the US was permitted.

00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:11.560
At issue in these cases
was not just race

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:13.960
and religion, as we will discover.

00:27:13.960 --> 00:27:26.110
According to Ian Hani Lopez, a
critical race and legal scholar,

00:27:26.110 --> 00:27:29.400
there are 4 main types
of arguments for

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:33.450
and against determining
whether the Syrians were white.

00:27:33.450 --> 00:27:36.950
Scientific evidence,
congressional intent,

00:27:36.950 --> 00:27:39.920
common knowledge, and
legal precedent.

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:42.430
The scientific evidence
claims were rooted

00:27:42.430 --> 00:27:46.310
in racial development theories
that examine the biological origins

00:27:46.310 --> 00:27:49.360
of the human and white race.

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:53.530
Judges deliberated over and weighed
arguments over the differences

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:55.920
between white and Caucasian.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:28:01.290 position:56%
And in the case of Nojor and Madari,
Syrians were found to be Semites.

00:28:01.290 --> 00:28:05.680
Semites were Caucasian,
and Caucasians were white.

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:09.160 position:56%
In the congressional intent
arguments, the intent of the authors

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:12.090
of the Naturalization
Act were examined.

00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:16.810
Since most free white
persons in 1790 were European,

00:28:16.810 --> 00:28:20.310
the question revolved around
whether Syrians were qualified

00:28:20.310 --> 00:28:23.750
to be free white persons
as Congress had attended

00:28:23.750 --> 00:28:26.300
or whether common knowledge
of today dictated

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:29.300
that the Syrians were
or were not white.

00:28:30.530 --> 00:28:34.120
I will argue that there were
more significant factors

00:28:34.120 --> 00:28:38.120
in determining the race of the
Syrians, and later the Arabians.

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:42.610
Primary among these was a choice,
a strategy, to distance themselves

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:46.280
from Asian-ness, even though
Syria was technically located

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:51.160
in Western Asia, and to place
their origins closer to Europe.

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:54.340
The mental geography of
this choice was a key

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:57.070
in establishing their
legal claims to whiteness.

00:28:57.070 --> 00:29:02.350
For the Syrians, there was also a
distancing from traits associated

00:29:02.350 --> 00:29:05.450
with Islam that were believed
at the time to be unassailable

00:29:05.450 --> 00:29:16.250
into the American polity, namely
polygamy and a Democratic mind.

00:29:16.250 --> 00:29:17.940
So there were alternative framings

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:21.840
for racial determinations,
in my analysis.

00:29:21.840 --> 00:29:26.100
In 1909, George Shishim, a
policeman in Venice, California,

00:29:26.100 --> 00:29:28.550
arrested a young man for
disturbing the peace.

00:29:28.550 --> 00:29:33.320
The young man's father, a prominent
lawyer, challenged Shishim's right

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:37.170
to arrest his son on the
basis that Shishim was not

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:40.320
and could not be a US citizen.

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:43.860
Although Shishim had lived in
California for about 20 years,

00:29:43.860 --> 00:29:47.280
his naturalization was in
question due to his origins

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:51.640
in the Ottoman Empire's
lands called Turkey, in Asia.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:55.690
Friends pulled their resources
and hired a lawyer, Byron Hanna,

00:29:55.690 --> 00:29:58.970
a fellow countrymen,
to defend Shishim.

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:02.660
As part of their case, they wrote
to academics and universities

00:30:02.660 --> 00:30:06.900
to inquire about the ethnological
background of their ancestry,

00:30:06.900 --> 00:30:08.950
and argued that Syrians
were Christians --

00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:11.450
Syrians were Caucasian, sorry.

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:14.770
In the final court hearing,
Shishim declared to the judge,

00:30:14.770 --> 00:30:19.940
and I do love this quote, "If I
am Mongolian, then so was Jesus,

00:30:19.940 --> 00:30:23.220 position:56%
because we came from the same land."

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:27.240
In fact, the way in which Shishim
articulated his origins claimed a

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:31.490
more authentic Christianity,
rooted in the land of the Bible.

00:30:31.490 --> 00:30:33.400
A Christianity that
was more authentic

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:36.860
than the judge's presumed
Christianity as a Protestant.

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:40.480
This line of reasoning dovetailed
with the racial ideology in the US

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:44.530
that had hallmarked Jesus
as white at the time.

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:48.320
The judge dismissed religion as
a factor that determined race.

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:52.860
But Shishim's declaration convinced
the judge that he was not Asian.

00:30:52.860 --> 00:30:54.610 position:56%
And he ruled that Shishim was white,

00:30:54.610 --> 00:30:57.430
and therefore eligible
for citizenship.

00:30:57.430 --> 00:31:02.450
After the decision was read, George
Shishim took his oath of allegiance

00:31:02.450 --> 00:31:05.990
to the United States
before he left the court.

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:11.520
Despite this ruling, the
Bureau of Immigration

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:13.580
and Naturalization continued

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:16.690
to deny some Syrian
Americans US citizenship,

00:31:16.690 --> 00:31:18.590
and naturalization therefore.

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:21.780
Many of the legal arguments in
the early cases regarding the race

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:25.160
of Arab-Americans centered
on being from the holy land

00:31:25.160 --> 00:31:29.490
and a practicing Christian of good
morals, sober, and industrious.

00:31:29.490 --> 00:31:32.850 position:56%
There's many legal cases about this.

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:35.420
By indicating to the court
that they were Christians,

00:31:35.420 --> 00:31:38.910
early Arab-Americans were
distancing themselves from Islam.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:42.200
This was a strategy based on the
negative image of Islam in the eyes

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:45.320
of immigration specialists
and judges

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:48.090
who were practically
concerned with the polygamy

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:51.370
and its associative immorality.

00:31:51.370 --> 00:31:55.710
In these cases, polygamy
was associated with Muslim,

00:31:55.710 --> 00:31:57.600
and was considered unassailable.

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:01.930
In fact, some Syrians had been
turned away at Ellis Island

00:32:01.930 --> 00:32:04.640
and other ports of entry
because they were Muslim,

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:07.740
and therefore potentially
polygamists, regardless of whether

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:09.460
or not they were married.

00:32:09.460 --> 00:32:12.080
There's a story of a 15-year-old
boy who was turned away

00:32:12.080 --> 00:32:17.610
because he was Muslim, because
he could become polygamist.

00:32:17.610 --> 00:32:20.040
These laws were originally
put on the books actually

00:32:20.040 --> 00:32:24.690
to exclude Mormons, not
Muslims, in another note.

00:32:24.690 --> 00:32:27.810
In some ways I agree with the
legal scholar Khaled Beydoun

00:32:27.810 --> 00:32:31.660
that there were clear cognitive
links made in these cases.

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:35.000
He argues, Muslims were
presumed to be nonwhite,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.480
and Arabs were presumed
to be Muslims.

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:41.670
Arabs were presumptively
ineligible for citizenship.

00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:46.030
There was a conflation
of Arab and Muslim,

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:48.910
